page.title: 02The Landscape
page.content: This is dominated by Stickle Pike (1231 ft.) which is just outside the area and Great Stickle (1001 ft.) just inside. The area consists of steep sided valleys with small streams cutting deep into them. The major river cutting the area in two diagonally from top right to bottom left is the Lickle, a fine trout river. The sides of the valleys are for the most part open fell punctuated by craggy outcrops of rock with the occasional sites of quarries spewing spoil down the fellside. In the valley bottoms are located farms which for the most part farm sheep on the fells and grow silage and hay on the better lowland fields for their winter keep. There are also many patches of deciduous woodland and the area is bordered on the east by a huge coniferous forest.
